            <title>Wednesday Week 8 - Solving Trigonometric Equations</title>
<page>
        <objectives>
          <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Find solutions to trigonometric equations using inverse trigonometric functions.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Find additional solutions in an indicated interval using the unit circle or a graph.
                </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </objectives>

<paragraphs>
    <title>Strategy for finding all solutions on an indicated domain</title>
    <p>
        Given an equation involving trigonometric functions, there are usually multiple solutions. To find them all on a given domain, the following is a good approach:
    </p>   
    <ul>
        <li>
            <p>
                Find at least one solution by doing algebra and using an inverse trigonometric function.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Use a graph or the unit circle to find solutions in the indicated domain.
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        When the equation involves trigonometric functions with only ``outside'' transformations applied, you can usually use the unit circle.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        When the equation involves trigonometric functions with ``inside'' transformations applied, it is often more useful to use a graph.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </li>
    </ul>

</paragraphs>

<example>
    <statement><title>Warm-up Question</title>
        <p workspace="3in">
            Find all solutions with <m>0\leq x &lt; 2\pi</m> to the equation
<md>
4\cos(2x) + 1 = 3. 
</md>
        </p>
    </statement>

</example>


</page>
<page>

<paragraphs>
    <title>Problems</title>
<p>
Find all solutions to the given equation on the indicated domain.   
</p>
<ol>
    <li>
        <p workspace="2.5in">
            <m>\tan^2(x) = 3</m> with <m>0\leq x &lt; 2\pi</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p workspace="2.5in">
            <m>6\sin(x) = 1</m> with <m>-3\pi\leq x &lt; 3\pi</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p workspace="2.5in">
            <m>2\sin\left(\pi\left(x+\frac{1}{3}\right)\right) + 5 = 4</m> with <m>0\leq x &lt; 2</m>.
        </p>
    </li>

</ol>

</paragraphs>   



